---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Bus Service Frequency Changes in Tel Aviv: 2022–2024"
  year="2024"
  category="Public Transport Analysis · Temporal GIS"
  tools={['Python', 'GTFS', 'GeoPandas', 'QGIS', 'Choropleth Mapping']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Overview</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Service frequency — how often a bus arrives — is one of the most direct measures of
        public transport quality. For riders, a bus that comes every 8 minutes versus every 20 minutes
        is the difference between a usable service and one you have to plan around. Tracking how
        frequency changes over time, and where, reveals which areas are getting better service and
        which are being left behind.
      </p>
      <p>
        This analysis used GTFS (General Transit Feed Specification) data to compute average
        headways by route segment across three time periods: 2022, 2023, and 2024. Changes in
        frequency were mapped at the route-segment level, using a diverging color scheme to clearly
        distinguish improvements (more frequent service) from degradations (less frequent service).
      </p>
      <p>
        The year-over-year maps revealed both system-wide trends and localized changes tied to
        specific route restructurings and the ongoing integration of the new light rail network,
        which absorbed some bus demand while triggering adjustments to connecting routes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps — Year-over-Year Frequency Change</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/freq-2022-2023.jpg`}
      alt="Map of bus service frequency changes in Tel Aviv between 2022 and 2023"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      2022 → 2023: Route segments colored by change in service frequency. Green = improved headways; red = reduced frequency.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/freq-2023-2024.jpg`}
      alt="Map of bus service frequency changes in Tel Aviv between 2023 and 2024"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      2023 → 2024: Continued restructuring visible as light rail integration proceeded, with notable frequency gains on trunk corridors.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/freq-2024.jpg`}
      alt="Map of bus service frequency in Tel Aviv, 2024"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      2024 state: Current service frequency baseline across the network.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methods</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        GTFS feeds were processed in Python to extract scheduled trip frequencies by route and
        time period (AM peak, PM peak, off-peak). Average headways were computed per route segment
        for each year. Segments were matched across years using route identifiers, and the delta
        in headway was calculated as the primary change metric.
      </p>
      <p>
        Route geometries from the GTFS shapes files were joined with the computed headway changes
        using GeoPandas. Diverging choropleth maps were produced in QGIS with a neutral midpoint
        at zero change, allowing direct visual comparison of the three periods.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>
